<subSubSection id="C34D656DFF83FFF8FF07FEB8FC69FE63" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BE836E6FF83FFF8FF07FEB8FC86FEB4" blockId="36.[151,1437,151,544]" box="[199,847,303,328]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis id="B923EAF4FF83FFF8FF07FEB8FE1BFEBB" bold="true" box="[199,466,303,328]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Global maximum size.</emphasis>
Maximum test diameter 
<quantity id="4CAF9B03FF83FFF8FD2BFEA7FC82FEB4" box="[747,843,304,328]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" unit="mm" value="100.0">100 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE836E6FF83FFF8FF07FEC4FC69FE63" blockId="36.[151,1437,151,544]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis id="B923EAF4FF83FFF8FF07FEC4FE7FFE9F" bold="true" box="[199,438,339,364]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Global distribution.</emphasis>
East coast region of South Africa, East Africa to Red Sea (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC64B17FF83FFF8FBADFEC4FAA8FE9F" author="Clark" box="[1133,1377,339,364]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" refString="Clark, A. M. &amp; Rowe, F. W. E. (1971) Monograph of Shallow-water Indo-West Pacific Echinoderms. Trustees of the British Museum, London, pp. 238." type="book chapter" year="1971">Clark &amp; Rowe, 1971</bibRefCitation>
) and Ceylon to Java and Phillipines, from littoral to 
<quantity id="4CAF9B03FF83FFF8FD65FEEFFD24FE7C" box="[677,749,376,400]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" unit="m" value="120.0">120 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFC64B17FF83FFF8FD3BFEE0FC5CFE63" author="Schultz" box="[763,917,375,400]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" refString="Schultz, H. (2010) Sea-Urchins, a Guide to Worldwide Shallow Water Species. 3 rd Edition. Scientific Publication, Hemdingen, 484 pp." type="book" year="2010">Schultz 2010</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34D656DFF83FFF8FF07FE0CFA8FFDEC" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BE836E6FF83FFF8FF07FE0CFA8FFDEC" blockId="36.[151,1437,151,544]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis id="B923EAF4FF83FFF8FF07FE0CFEF2FE47" bold="true" box="[199,315,411,436]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Remarks.</emphasis>
Closely resembles 
<taxonomicName id="4C574D65FF83FFF8FDDCFE0CFCD2FE47" authorityName=": Schultz" authorityYear="2010" box="[540,795,411,436]" class="Echinoidea" family="Temnopleuridae" genus="Salmaciella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Camarodonta" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="erythracis">
<emphasis id="B923EAF4FF83FFF8FDDCFE0CFCD2FE47" box="[540,795,411,436]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Salmaciella erythracis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs in test shape, apical disc and appearance of ambulacral tubercles. 
<taxonomicName id="4C574D65FF83FFF8FE58FE57FDF1FE2B" box="[408,568,447,472]" class="Echinoidea" family="Temnopleuridae" genus="Salmaciella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Camarodonta" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="eryhthracis">
<emphasis id="B923EAF4FF83FFF8FE58FE57FDF1FE2B" box="[408,568,447,472]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">S. eryhthracis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a low test, anal opening eccentrically positioned towards periproctal margin and ambulacral tubercles reduced on alternating plates towards the aboral side; whilst 
<taxonomicName id="4C574D65FF83FFF8FB24FE73FA9CFE0F" authorityName=": H. L. Clark" authorityYear="1923" box="[1252,1365,483,508]" class="Echinoidea" family="Temnopleuridae" genus="Salmacis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Camarodonta" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis id="B923EAF4FF83FFF8FB24FE73FA9CFE0F" box="[1252,1365,483,508]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">S. bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a conically test, a periproct surrounded by tubercles and large tubercles disappearing towards the apical area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
